I set my version up with a -f on the unmark rm so that I don&#x27;t need to be prompted to remove it. Also added some basic completion for both jump and unmark<p><pre><code>  export MARKPATH=$HOME/.marks
  function jump { 
      cd -P $MARKPATH/$1 2>/dev/null || echo &quot;No such mark: $1&quot;
  }
  function mark { 
      mkdir -p $MARKPATH; ln -s $(pwd) $MARKPATH/$1
  }
  function unmark { 
      rm -if $MARKPATH/$1 
  }
  function marks {
      ls -l $MARKPATH | sed &#x27;s/  / /g&#x27; | cut -d&#x27; &#x27; -f9- | sed &#x27;s/ -/	-/g&#x27; && echo
  }

  _completemarks() {
      local curw=${COMP_WORDS[COMP_CWORD]}
      local wordlist=$(find $MARKPATH -type l -printf &quot;%f
&quot;)
      COMPREPLY=($(compgen -W &#x27;${wordlist[@]}&#x27; -- &quot;$curw&quot;))
      return 0
  }

  complete -F _completemarks jump unmark</code></pre>

Break out a shell, I live <i>in the shell</i>?<p>Servers don&#x27;t have a GUI and I do about 90% of administration from the command line on the Desktops/Laptops (the only time I use a GUI for configuration is to configure the GUI..meta).<p>Linux isn&#x27;t Windows or Mac, The command line is <i>expected</i> to be used for administration (and this approach has <i>lots</i> of benefits, script-ability, reproducibility, the ability to send the same command to 50 identical servers to name a few).<p>The unix (linux/freeBSD) command line is one of it&#x27;s stand-out features (others been stability, cost and ease of deployment.<p>I&#x27;ve yet to find a GUI that allows me to manipulate files and data in a general way that matches the linux command line, take this for example.<p><pre><code>    #!/bin/bash

    php artisan routes | grep -i $1 |sort -k 4 | cut -d &#x27;|&#x27; -f 3 | sed &#x27;s/ GET //&#x27; | while read ln; 
    do 

    	filename=${ln//[/]/_}.png; 
    	echo $filename;
    	cutycapt --url=http://metaflow.co.uk&quot;$ln&quot; --out=/home/dev/screenshots/$filename --min-width=1280 --min-height=1280; 
    done
</code></pre>
(not this script is a hack job, bash-aficionados can wince now)
That dumps out a list of all the routes in my currently developed webapp then loops over them converting the url to a sensible filename (/add/customer becomes _add_customer.png etc) then it uses a command line utility to visit that URL and grap an image of the page at 1280x1280 (using the webkit engine) and saves them in a folder in my home folder.<p>With a single command I can dump 50 mock screens to png and name them with the URL and I can do this <i>every time I change them</i> automatically.<p>This is what my home desktop looks like on a typical day <a href="http://i.imgur.com/vLMVAI8.png" rel="nofollow">http://i.imgur.com/vLMVAI8.png</a>
